{"cursor":"12873","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nA 'segmentation fault' (often shortened to 'segfault'), 'bus error' or 'access\nviolation' is generally an attempt to access memory that the CPU cannot\nphysically address. It occurs when the hardware notifies an operating system\nabout a memory access violation. The OS kernel then sends a signal to the\nprocess which caused the exception. By default, the process receiving the signal\ndumps core and terminates. The default signal handler can also be overridden to\ncustomize how the signal is handled. Expert C\nprogramming: deep C secrets By Peter Van der Linden, page 188\n","linknr":303,"url":"Bus_error","recorded":1362891453,"links":30,"instances":["operating_system","programming","computer_science","computing","computing","programming_language","website","computing","computer_programming"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Computer buses","Memory management","Operating system technology","Computer errors","Articles with example C code"],"headings":["Bus error","Segmentation, page fault, and access violation","Handling","Examples","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/FreeBSD_kernel_panic.png/220px-FreeBSD_kernel_panic.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/49/Windows_null_ptr_dereference.png/220px-Windows_null_ptr_dereference.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/26/Card_reader_segfault.jpg/220px-Card_reader_segfault.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1